Labeled dataframe¶

The original thyroid disease (ann-thyroid) dataset from UCI machine learning repository is a classification dataset, which is suited for training ANNs. It has 3772 training instances and 3428 testing instances. It has 15 categorical and 6 real attributes. The problem is to determine whether a patient referred to the clinic is hypothyroid. Therefore three classes are built: normal (not hypothyroid), hyperfunction and subnormal functioning. For outlier detection, 3772 training instances are used, with only 6 real attributes. The hyperfunction class is treated as outlier class and other two classes are inliers, because hyperfunction is a clear minority class.

from statistics import stdev

def get_outliers_for_given_feature(df, feature):
    q1, q3 = np.percentile(df[feature], [25,75])
    iqr = q3 - q1
    lower_bound = q1 - (1.5 * iqr) 
    upper_bound = q3 + (1.5 * iqr) 
    return [(value < lower_bound) or (value > upper_bound) for value in list(df[feature])]

def outliers_mean_sd(df, feature):
    lower_bound = np.mean(df[feature]) - 3 * stdev(df[feature])
    upper_bound = np.mean(df[feature]) + 3 * stdev(df[feature])
    return [(value < lower_bound) or (value > upper_bound) for value in list(df[feature])]

def incorrecty_detected_percentage(pred_outliers):
    incorrect = 0
    true_outliers = list(df_thyroid['Outlier'])
    for i in range(len(true_outliers)):
        if true_outliers[i] != pred_outliers[i]:
            incorrect += 1
    return incorrect / len(true_outliers) * 100

def get_detection_results_on_labeled_df(feature, pred_outliers, visualization=True):
    if visualization:
        see_data_distribution(df_thyroid, column_name)
    
    print(feature + '  -----------------  ' + str(incorrecty_detected_percentage(pred_outliers)) + 
          '% from the samples were incorrectly detected')
    
    print('\n_______________ Detection Report _______________\n\n', 
          classification_report(list(df_thyroid['Outlier']), pred_outliers))
    print('________________________________________________________________________________________________\n\n')

    
print('__________________________________________1.5 IQR RULE___________________________________________') 
for column_name in features:
    outliers_iqr = get_outliers_for_given_feature(df_thyroid, column_name)
    get_detection_results_on_labeled_df(column_name, outliers_iqr)
    
    
print('__________________________________________mean +/- k*sd ___________________________________________') 
for column_name in features:
    outliers_iqr = outliers_mean_sd(df_thyroid, column_name)
    get_detection_results_on_labeled_df(column_name, outliers_iqr)

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

def biplot(score, coeff, color_array, xlim, ylim, ids=[1, 2], labels=None):
    xs = score[:,0]
    ys = score[:,1]
    n = coeff.shape[0]
    
    scalex = 1.0/(xs.max() - xs.min())
    scaley = 1.0/(ys.max() - ys.min())
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12,12))
    maximum = max(color_array)
    
    plt.scatter(xs * scalex,ys * scaley, c = [plt.cm.jet(float(i)/maximum) for i in color_array],
                edgecolors='k', s=30)
    for i in range(n):
        plt.arrow(0, 0, coeff[i,0], coeff[i,1], color = 'r', alpha = 0.5)
        if labels is None:
            plt.text(coeff[i,0]* 1.15, coeff[i,1] * 1.15, "Var"+str(i+1), color = 'g', ha = 'center', va = 'center')
        else:
            plt.text(coeff[i,0]* 1.15, coeff[i,1] * 1.15, labels[i], color = 'g', ha = 'center', va = 'center')

    plt.title('Principal Components Analysis visualization')
    plt.xlim(*xlim)
    plt.ylim(*ylim)
    plt.xlabel("PrincipalComponent{}".format(ids[0]))
    plt.ylabel("PrincipalComponent{}".format(ids[1]))
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()

# Compute the euclidean distance using the first 5 PC
euclidean = np.zeros(df_thyroid[features].shape[0])
for i in range(5):
    euclidean += (pca_data[:,i] - np.mean(pca_data[:,:5]))**2/np.var(pca_data[:,:5])

def see_outliers_based_on_distance(distances, pca_data, xlim, ylim):
    colors = [plt.cm.jet(float(i)/max(distances)) for i in distances]

    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    with plt.style.context(('ggplot')):
        plt.scatter(pca_data[:, 0], pca_data[:, 1], c=colors, edgecolors='k', s=60)
        plt.xlabel('PC1')
        plt.ylabel('PC2')
        plt.xlim(*xlim)
        plt.ylim(*ylim)
        plt.title('Score Plot')
    plt.show()
    
see_outliers_based_on_distance(euclidean, pca_data, [-10, 12], [-10, 12])

As it can be noticed, the points towards the edges of along PC1 tends to have larger distances. More or less as expected. In practice Euclidean distance puts more weight than it should on correlated variables.

The major problem with the approach above is in the calculation of mean and standard deviation. If we really had outliers in our data, they would definitely skew the calculation of mean and standard deviation.

Mahalanobis distance is very similar to the Euclidean distance, except each element of the summation is weighted by the corresponding element of the covariance matrix of the data. The details of the calculation are not really needed, as scikit-learn has a handy function to calculate the Mahalanobis distance based on a robust estimation of the covariance matrix.

In [22]:
from sklearn.covariance import EmpiricalCovariance, MinCovDet

# fit a Minimum Covariance Determinant (MCD) robust estimator to data 
robust_cov = MinCovDet().fit(pca_data[:,:5])

# Get the Mahalanobis distance
mahalanobis_distances = robust_cov.mahalanobis(pca_data[:,:5])

see_outliers_based_on_distance(mahalanobis_distances, pca_data, [-10, 12], [-10, 12])

def search_threshold_exhaustively(threshold_values, labeled_df=True):
    percentages = []
    outliers_no = []
    for value in threshold_values:
        pred_outliers = [distance < value for distance in mahalanobis_distances]
        if labeled_df:
            print(Counter(pred_outliers))
            get_detection_results_on_labeled_df('Mahalanobis distance detection', pred_outliers, False)
            percentages.append(incorrecty_detected_percentage(pred_outliers))
        else:
            outliers_no.append(sum(pred_outliers))
    return outliers_no

search_threshold_exhaustively([10, 5, 2, 0.6, 1e-1])

Local outlier factor¶

The Local Outlier Factor (LOF) algorithm is an unsupervised anomaly detection method which computes the local density deviation of a given data point with respect to its neighbors. It considers as outliers the samples that have a substantially lower density than their neighbors.

from sklearn.neighbors import LocalOutlierFactor

scaled_x = StandardScaler().fit_transform(df_thyroid[features])
scaled_x = pd.DataFrame(scaled_x, columns=features)


def build_lof_model(df, n_neighbors, contamination, features, labeled=True):
    scaled_x = StandardScaler().fit_transform(df[features])
    scaled_x = pd.DataFrame(scaled_x, columns=features)
    
    clf = LocalOutlierFactor(n_neighbors=n_neighbors, contamination=contamination)
    y_pred = clf.fit_predict(scaled_x[features])
    outliers_pred = [1 if y == -1 else 0 for y in y_pred]
    X_scores = clf.negative_outlier_factor_
    if labeled:
        return incorrecty_detected_percentage(outliers_pred), Counter(outliers_pred), X_scores, outliers_pred, clf
    else:
        return Counter(outliers_pred), X_scores, outliers_pred, clf

def pursue_exhausive_search_for_given_combination_of_features(df, features, labeled=True):
    config_results = dict()
    for n_neighbors in [1, 3, 4, 6, 10, 100]:
        for contamination in [0.03, 0.05, 0.1, 0.3]:
            config_results[(n_neighbors, contamination)] = build_lof_model(df, n_neighbors, contamination,features)[:2]
    if labeled:
        config_results = sorted(config_results.items(), key=lambda kv: kv[1])
    return config_results

Outliers detection using decession trees: Isolation Forest¶

The IsolationForest ‘isolates’ observations by randomly selecting a feature and then randomly selecting a split value between the maximum and minimum values of the selected feature.

Since recursive partitioning can be represented by a tree structure, the number of splittings required to isolate a sample is equivalent to the path length from the root node to the terminating node.

This path length, averaged over a forest of such random trees, is a measure of normality and our decision function.

Random partitioning produces noticeable shorter paths for anomalies. Hence, when a forest of random trees collectively produce shorter path lengths for particular samples, they are highly likely to be anomalies.

On labeled dataframe¶

Isolation Forest using all of the independent variables¶
In [39]:
from sklearn.ensemble import IsolationForest

def get_incorrectly_classif_perc_isol_forest_givem_min_samples(df, max_samples, features, labeled=True):
    clf = IsolationForest(max_samples=max_samples, random_state=0)
    
    y_pred = clf.fit_predict(df[features]) # 1 for inliers, -1 for outliers
    outliers_pred = [1 if y == -1 else 0 for y in y_pred]
    if labeled:
        return incorrecty_detected_percentage(outliers_pred), Counter(outliers_pred), outliers_pred, clf
    else:
        return Counter(outliers_pred), outliers_pred, clf

Another methods for anomaly detection¶

  • projection methods: Stahel-Donoho extensions for asymmetrical distributions
  • autoencoders: https://towardsdatascience.com/anomaly-detection-with-autoencoder-b4cdce4866a6
